Exploratory Data Analysis of the Red Wine

Ravinder Bahra

April 15th 2018

Introduction

The following report uses the public red wine dataset collected for the report titled Modeling wine preferences by data mining from physicochemical properties by Paulo Cortez.

The dataset consists of 1599 samples, 11 input variables which are based on physiochemical properties of the wine and 1 output variable which is the quality of the wine. The quality of the wine was based on sensory data (taste).

3 wine experts assessed and rated the quality of the wine, a score between 0 to 10 was given where 0 is very bad and 10 is very good.

This report will investigate which of these properties impacts the quality of the wine.

The table shows that all of the data is numerical, we have the following physicochemical properties we can use to explore the dataset. Some of the explanations for the properites were given as part of the dataset.

  • Fixed Acidity - Represents the non volatile acids in the wine
  • Volatile Acidity - Too high can results in a vinegar like taste (unpleasant)
  • Citric Acid - adds flavour to the wine
  • Residual Sugar - The sugar left after the fementation process. Large amounts are found in sweeter wines
  • Chlorides - salt content
  • Free Sulfur Dioxide - used to prevent microbial growth and prevents the wine from oxidizing
  • Density - density of the liquid. Denisity of water is 0.997 g/m3
  • pH - The acidity of the wine, lower values on the ph scale are more acidic (higher is alkaline). According to the information given with the dataset well find most wines have a ph between 3-4
  • Sulphates - added to the wine to increase the sulfur dioxide gas level. Sulfur dioxide gas is an antimicrobial (agent that kills microorganisms )
  • Alcohol - The % of alcohol in the wine

Distributions of wine properties

The following code will loop over the column names and generate histograns of all the wine properties

# this code will iterate over all columns/properties in the dataset and create
# a distribution. The distributions wll be added to a list. This list will be
# passed to grid.arrange to arrange a grid view of all the distribution plots

# pull all the names of the columns into a vector variable
column_names <- names(wine_dataset)

# create an empty list to store the plots 
plot_list <- list()

# iterate over the column names and create a plot for each property
for (i in 1:length(column_names)){
  # generate a histogram and add to the list
  plot_list[[i]] <- ggplot(aes_string(x=column_names[i]), data=wine_dataset) +
    geom_histogram(bins=30)
}
# pass the list to grid.arrange to display all pl
grid.arrange(grobs = plot_list, ncol = floor(sqrt(length(column_names))))

Univariate Analysis

Looking at the distribution of the wine quality, most of the wines were rated 5/10 - 6/10.

Most of the distributions are positively skewed, density, ph and quality appear normally distributed.

Citric acid shows a bimodal distribution.

Looking at the summary statistics for each physicochemical property, some of the propeties have a lot of outliers. The most notiable from the distributions and the summary statistics are

  • residual sugar
  • chlorides
  • total sulfur dioxide
  • sulphates

In the bivariate section we can begin to look at how these variables effect each other to determine what properties effect the quality.

Bivariate Analysis

Now we will look at multiple variables together. Pairwuise plots are a good way to see what variables correlate together

# The function scatter_func returns a scatter plot with the addition of a 
# regression line. The default behavior is over ridden by passing a function
# as a parameter in ggpairs

scatter_func <- function(data, mapping,...){
  p <- ggplot(data=data, mapping = mapping) +
    # add alpha level to the plot
    geom_point(alpha=0.01) +
    # add a regression line
    geom_smooth(method = "lm", se = FALSE) +
    #reduce the size of the text so it doesn't overlap
    theme(text = element_text(size=8),
        axis.text.x = element_text(angle=90))
}

colnames <- names(wine_dataset)[1:length(names(wine_dataset))]

ggpairs(wine_dataset,
        columns = 1:ncol(wine_dataset),
        upper = list(continuous = wrap("cor", size = 2.5)),
        lower = list(continuous = scatter_func),
        columnLabels = gsub('.', ' ', colnames, fixed = T),
        labeller = label_wrap_gen(10)
        #diag = list(continuous = diag_func)
        )

Which variables impact quality

The output variable (quality) is of most interest to us, wed like to determine which properties of the wine contribute to a greater quality

There are some properties that do correlate with quality. The correlations are not strong but do stand out and are worth looking into for further analysis.

The properties that stood out against quality the most are as follows

  • Alcohol content (+0.476)
  • Volatile acidity (-3.91)
  • sulphate (+0.251)
  • Citric acid (+0.226)

Other correlations not against quality are as follows

  • Total Sulfur Dioxide and Free Sulphur Dioxide corrlate, which isnt unexpected as total sulfur dioxide contains free sulfur dioxide
  • Citric Acid and Fixed Acidity (0.672) - again this is expected with larger volumes of acid
  • pH with Citric Acid (-0.542) and pH with Fixed Acidity (-0.683) - again will correlate, higher acidity has a lower PH (higher Ph is more alkaline)
  • Citric Acid and Volatile Acidity (-0.552)
  • Alcohol Content and Density (-0.496)
  • Density and Residual Sugar (0.355)
  • Density and pH (-0.342)

# create a new variable to hold factor version of quality
wine_dataset$quality_factors <- as.factor(wine_dataset$quality)

# create box plots for each property

scatter plots

code for plotting scatter plots and histograms

# the following code allows us to pass in a property and it will create a 
# scatter plot
quality_scatter <- function(wine_property){
  plt <- ggplot(aes_string(x='quality',y=wine_property),data=wine_dataset) +
  geom_point(position='jitter', aes(color=quality), alpha=0.3) +
  geom_smooth(method = 'lm')
  return(plt)
}

# the function creates faceted historgrams which are split by the quality of the
# wine
wine_property_hist <- function(wine_property){
  plt <- ggplot(aes_string(x=wine_property), data=wine_dataset) +
  geom_histogram() +
  #geom_histogram(aes(fill=quality_factors)) +
  facet_wrap(~quality_factors)
  return(plt)
}

Bivariate Plots Analysis

I was surprised to see that residual sugar didnt correlate with quality. I initially had presumptions that sweeter wines would score higher on quality.

Even removing the outliers did not improve the correlation.

It was noticed that increased alcohol decreases the density of the wine. This is due to the fact that alcohol is less dense than water. This could indicate that less dense wines are seen as better quality

The intial box plots shows the distributions for different quality ratings. An increase in alcohol did show an increase in quality. Is this because of the alcohol content or is the fact the increase in alcohol reduces the density of the liquid.

An increase in citric acid also showed an increase in quality
